    seedDRAFT.txt

    This is a peer-to-peer file sharing system written in C++ that implements distributed seeding and downloading across multiple network ports. Here's the detailed flow:

    System Architecture

    The program creates a hybrid server-client where each instance:

    • Acts as a server: Listens on a port (9005-9009) and shares files from its local seed folder
    • Acts as a client: Discovers and downloads files from other active seeders

    Core Data Structures

    struct FileInfo { std::string filepath; // Full path to file std::string key_id; // Directory name (used as file group identifier) size_t file_size; // File size in bytes std::string seed_info; // Display information int source_port; // Which port this file came from }; struct ChunkDownload { int chunk_id; // Chunk sequence number int port; // Source port for this chunk size_t start_offset; // Byte offset in original file size_t chunk_size; // Size (32 bytes max) std::vector<char> data; // Actual chunk data bool completed; // Download status };

    Program Flow

    1. Initialization Phase

    int main() { // Find available port (9005-9009) int port = find_available_port(server_fd, address); // Start server thread to handle incoming requests pthread_create(&tid, nullptr, server_thread, &server_fd); // Enter interactive menu loop while (true) { show_menu(); } }

    2. Server Thread (Continuous)

    void *server_thread(void *arg) { while (true) { // Accept incoming client connections int client_socket = accept(server_fd, ...); // Spawn thread for each client pthread_create(&client_thread, nullptr, handle_client, client_data); } }

    3. Client Request Handling

    Each client request is handled by handle_client():

    A. LIST_FILES Request:

    if (request == "LIST_FILES") { // Get local files from current seed folder std::vector<FileInfo> local_files = get_local_files(current_port); // Send file list: "filepath|key_id|size|seed_info" send_all(client_socket, response.c_str(), response.size()); }

    B. DOWNLOAD_CHUNK Request:

    if (request.substr(0, 14) == "DOWNLOAD_CHUNK") { // Parse: "DOWNLOAD_CHUNK|filepath|start_offset|chunk_size" // Read specific chunk from file std::ifstream file(filepath, std::ios::binary); file.seekg(start_offset); file.read(chunk_data, chunk_size); // Send chunk data back send_all(client_socket, chunk_data, bytes_read); }

    C. Interactive Download Request:

    • Discovers available files from all active ports
    • Presents file menu to user
    • Manages complete download process with progress tracking

    4. File Discovery Process

    // Menu Option 1: List Files std::vector<int> active_ports = get_active_ports(port); for (int active_port : active_ports) { // Request file list from each active seeder std::vector<FileInfo> port_files = request_files_from_port(active_port); // Deduplicate files by filename+size }

    5. Download Process (Most Complex)

    A. File Selection:

    // Group files by key_id (directory name) std::map<std::string, std::vector<FileInfo>> files_by_key_id; // User selects a key_id, gets all files in that group std::vector<FileInfo> &selected_files = files_by_key_id[selected_key_id];

    B. Parallel Download Execution:

    void download_files_background() { // For each selected file: for (const auto &selected_file : selected_files) { // 1. Calculate chunks needed size_t total_chunks = (file_size + CHUNK_SIZE - 1) / CHUNK_SIZE; // 2. Create chunk download tasks std::vector<ChunkDownload> chunks; for (size_t i = 0; i < total_chunks; ++i) { // Distribute chunks across available ports (round-robin) int target_port = valid_source_ports[i % valid_source_ports.size()]; chunks.emplace_back(i, target_port, start_offset, chunk_size); } // 3. Download chunks in parallel (batched) const size_t MAX_CONCURRENT_CHUNKS = 10; while (chunks_processed < total_chunks) { // Process chunks in batches to avoid overwhelming network for (size_t i = 0; i < batch_size; ++i) { chunk_threads.emplace_back([&chunk, &selected_file]() { // Try original port, fallback to others if needed download_chunk_from_port(chunk.port, selected_file.filepath, chunk); }); } // Wait for batch completion for (auto& thread : chunk_threads) { thread.join(); } } // 4. Reassemble file from chunks std::ofstream outfile(final_path, std::ios::binary); for (const auto& chunk : chunks) { if (chunk.completed) { outfile.write(chunk.data.data(), chunk.data.size()); } } } }

    6. Key Features

    Chunk-Based Downloading:

    • Files split into 32-byte chunks for parallel downloading
    • Each chunk can come from different seeders
    • Fault tolerance: if one seeder fails, tries others

    Multi-Port Architecture:

    • Each instance uses ports 9005-9009
    • Port-to-seed folder mapping: {9005: "seed1", 9006: "seed2", ...}
    • Automatic discovery of active seeders

    Thread Safety:

    • Multiple mutexes for download state, progress tracking, console output
    • Atomic counters for progress tracking
    • Background downloads don't block UI

    Progress Tracking:

    • Real-time download progress with percentage completion
    • Status tracking for completed/failed downloads
    • Duplicate file handling with automatic renaming

    This system essentially creates a decentralized file sharing network where each instance contributes files and can download from others, with sophisticated chunk-based parallel downloading for efficiency.

    In-Depth Technical Analysis: P2P File Sharing System

    This is a sophisticated multi-threaded, chunk-based peer-to-peer file sharing system that implements a hybrid server-client architecture with advanced features like parallel downloading, fault tolerance, and real-time progress tracking.

    1. Network Architecture & Protocol Design

    Port Management Strategy

    #define START_PORT 9005 #define END_PORT 9009 std::map<int, std::string> port_to_seed = { {9005, "seed1"}, {9006, "seed2"}, {9007, "seed3"}, {9008, "seed4"}, {9009, "seed5"} };

    Port Discovery Algorithm:

    • Dynamic Port Allocation: find_available_port() iterates through ports 9005-9009
    • Socket Reuse: Uses SO_REUSEADDR to prevent "Address already in use" errors
    • Active Port Detection: is_port_active() uses TCP connection attempts to detect live seeders

    Custom Application Protocol

    The system implements a text-based request-response protocol:

    Protocol Messages:

    1. LIST_FILES Returns: filepath|key_id|size|seed_info\n
    2. DOWNLOAD_CHUNK|filepath|start_offset|chunk_size Returns: Binary chunk data
    3. Interactive Download Multi-step file selection and download coordination

    2. Threading Model & Concurrency Architecture

    Thread Hierarchy:

    Main Thread Server Thread (pthread) - Accepts connections Client Handler Thread 1 (pthread) Client Handler Thread 2 (pthread) Client Handler Thread N (pthread) Background Download Threads (std::thread) File Download Thread 1 Chunk Download Thread 1 Chunk Download Thread 2 ... (up to 10 concurrent) File Download Thread N

    Synchronization Mechanisms:

    std::mutex download_mutex; // Protects active_downloads map std::mutex progress_mutex; // Protects download progress tracking std::mutex console_mutex; // Prevents garbled console output std::atomic<size_t> downloaded_bytes; // Lock-free progress counters std::atomic<int> completed_chunks;

    Critical Section Analysis:

    • Download State: Protected by download_mutex to prevent duplicate downloads
    • Progress Tracking: progress_mutex ensures thread-safe progress updates
    • Atomic Operations: Used for performance-critical counters to avoid mutex overhead

    3. Memory Management & Data Structures

    Core Data Structures:

    FileInfo Structure:

    struct FileInfo { std::string filepath; // Full filesystem path std::string key_id; // Directory-based grouping identifier size_t file_size; // Exact byte count std::string seed_info; // Human-readable description int source_port; // Origin seeder port };

    ChunkDownload Structure:

    struct ChunkDownload { int chunk_id; // Sequential chunk identifier int port; // Target seeder port size_t start_offset; // Byte position in original file size_t chunk_size; // Actual chunk size (32 bytes) std::vector<char> data; // Dynamically allocated chunk buffer bool completed; // Atomic completion flag };

    Memory Optimization Strategies:

    • Fixed Chunk Size: 32-byte chunks minimize memory fragmentation
    • RAII Pattern: std::unique_ptr<ClientData> ensures automatic cleanup
    • Vector Reuse: Pre-allocated chunk vectors avoid repeated allocations

    4. Detailed Execution Flow Analysis

    A. System Initialization Sequence:

    int main() { // 1. Port Discovery & Socket Binding int port = find_available_port(server_fd, address); // 2. Server Thread Spawn pthread_create(&tid, nullptr, server_thread, &server_fd); // 3. Interactive Menu Loop while (true) { show_menu(); } }

    B. Server Thread Execution:

    void *server_thread(void *arg) { // Extract port from bound socket getsockname(server_fd, (sockaddr *)&addr, &len); current_port = ntohs(addr.sin_port); while (true) { // Accept incoming connection int client_socket = accept(server_fd, ...); // Spawn dedicated handler thread ClientData* data = new ClientData{client_socket, current_port}; pthread_create(&client_thread, nullptr, handle_client, data); pthread_detach(client_thread); // Auto-cleanup on completion } }

    C. Client Request Processing:

    LIST_FILES Handler:

    if (request == "LIST_FILES") { // 1. Scan local seed directory std::vector<FileInfo> local_files = get_local_files(current_port); // 2. Serialize file metadata for (const auto &file_info : local_files) { response += file_info.filepath + "|" + file_info.key_id + "|" + std::to_string(file_info.file_size) + "|" + file_info.seed_info + "\n"; } // 3. Send response send_all(client_socket, response.c_str(), response.size()); }

    DOWNLOAD_CHUNK Handler:

    if (request.substr(0, 14) == "DOWNLOAD_CHUNK") { // 1. Parse request parameters std::istringstream iss(request); std::getline(iss, filepath, '|'); std::getline(iss, start_str, '|'); std::getline(iss, size_str); // 2. File I/O with precise seeking std::ifstream file(filepath, std::ios::binary); file.seekg(start_offset); file.read(chunk_data, chunk_size); // 3. Binary data transmission send_all(client_socket, chunk_data, bytes_read); }

    5. Advanced Download Algorithm

    File Discovery & Deduplication:

    // 1. Multi-port file aggregation for (int active_port : active_ports) { std::vector<FileInfo> port_files = request_files_from_port(active_port); // 2. Deduplication by filename + size for (const FileInfo &file : port_files) { std::string file_key = extract_filename(file.filepath) + "|" + std::to_string(file.file_size); if (seen.count(file_key) == 0) { files.push_back(file); seen.insert(file_key); } } }

    Chunk Distribution Algorithm:

    // Round-robin chunk distribution across seeders for (size_t i = 0; i < total_chunks; ++i) { size_t start_offset = i * CHUNK_SIZE; size_t chunk_size = std::min(CHUNK_SIZE, file_size - start_offset); int target_port = valid_source_ports[i % valid_source_ports.size()]; chunks.emplace_back(i, target_port, start_offset, chunk_size); }

    Parallel Download with Batching:

    const size_t MAX_CONCURRENT_CHUNKS = 10; // Network congestion control while (chunks_processed < total_chunks) { size_t batch_size = std::min(MAX_CONCURRENT_CHUNKS, total_chunks - chunks_processed); // Spawn batch of download threads for (size_t i = 0; i < batch_size; ++i) { chunk_threads.emplace_back([&chunk, &selected_file]() { // Primary download attempt if (!download_chunk_from_port(chunk.port, selected_file.filepath, chunk)) { // Fallback to alternative seeders for (int fallback_port : valid_source_ports) { if (fallback_port == chunk.port) continue; if (download_chunk_from_port(fallback_port, ...)) break; } } }); } // Synchronization barrier for (auto& thread : chunk_threads) { thread.join(); } }

    6. Error Handling & Fault Tolerance

    Network Resilience:

    • Connection Timeouts: 10-second socket timeouts prevent hanging
    • Automatic Fallback: Failed chunk downloads retry on alternative seeders
    • Graceful Degradation: Partial downloads continue even if some seeders fail

    File System Safety:

    • Directory Creation: create_directory_recursive() ensures target paths exist
    • Duplicate Handling: Automatic filename collision resolution with _N suffixes
    • Atomic File Assembly: Complete file written only after all chunks succeed

    7. Performance Optimizations

    Network Efficiency:

    • Persistent Connections: Reused sockets for multiple chunk requests
    • Binary Protocol: Raw chunk data transmission without encoding overhead
    • Batched Operations: Controlled concurrency prevents network saturation

    Memory Efficiency:

    • Streaming I/O: Files processed in small chunks, not loaded entirely
    • Stack Allocation: Fixed-size buffers avoid heap fragmentation
    • RAII Cleanup: Automatic resource management prevents memory leaks

    CPU Optimization:

    • Lock-Free Counters: Atomic operations for high-frequency updates
    • Thread Pooling: Detached threads with automatic cleanup
    • Minimal Copying: Move semantics for large data structures

    8. Security Considerations

    Current Vulnerabilities:

    • No Authentication: Any client can access any file
    • Path Traversal: Potential directory traversal attacks
    • Resource Exhaustion: No rate limiting on connections or downloads

    Potential Mitigations:

    • Access Control Lists: Port-based or token-based authentication
    • Path Sanitization: Restrict file access to designated directories
    • Resource Limits: Connection throttling and bandwidth management

    This system demonstrates sophisticated distributed systems concepts including load balancing, fault tolerance, parallel processing, and real-time monitoring - making it an excellent foundation for understanding peer-to-peer networking architectures.
